    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i saw something in a forum about pitot tubes getting blocked though. what kind of stuff usually causes issues with them? like can anything tiny just get stuck in there and mess up the readings?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blocked pitot tubes are a serious hazard, and yes, even something tiny can cause a massive reading error, like a rogue piece of gravel or a very small piece of debris. Icy formations are a huge culprit, especially when the temperature drops, and even a small accumulation of frost can completely choke the opening. It's a real danger, as if a small pebble blocks the entrance to a vital part of a complex, it can throw the whole system into chaos, making the pilot think they are flying faster or slower than they actually are. You need to keep those tubes clear, or your airspeed indicator will be giving you garbage data, which is just as bad as a truly malfunctioning piece of equipment.",
